g.text: This design is hereby placed into the public domain
The original board had three banks of four 8k by 8 SRAM ICs.
Each of the 3 ~CS1~ bank lines went to the enable of a decoder for
each bank. The decoder selected ~CS1~ of an SRAM IC based on A13/A14.
In this design, a single 128k by 8 SRAM is used. An encoder combines
the 3 ~CS1~ bank lines into two address lines, leaving one 32k bank
It may be possible to use three 32k by 8 SRAMS and directly route
a ~CS1~ bank line to each. However this is not entirely consistent
with the original RAM module: in the original, when logic power
is cut (but SRAM power is still present), the ~CS1~ bank lines
can no longer drive the SRAM ~CS1~ lines. We maintain that
behavior with this circuit by having the ~CS1~ bank lines connect
through the 75HC148. Whether the behavior is required is unknown.
The original SRAM module had this AND gate circuit. It was not
clear what it is supposed to do so it has been retained. It appears
that perhaps it was supposed to pull SRAM ~OE~ and ~WE~ lines
low when logic power is removed. However when logic power
goes low, power to the AND gate is also cut. The original
board had a second unknown, unpopulated, 1206 component
footprint in parallel with the 10k resistor.
